      </div>

      <div class="verdict" id="quick-verdict">
        <strong>Quick verdict:</strong> The <strong>Logitech MX Master 3S</strong> is the best productivity mouse you can buy in 2026, full stop. The MagSpeed scroll wheel remains the benchmark, the new 8000 DPI sensor finally tracks on glass, and the quiet clicks are 90% quieter than the previous generation. At $99 it is not cheap, but for anyone who spends six or more hours a day at the computer, it pays for itself in comfort.
      </div>

      <p>Logitech launched the MX Master 3 in 2019, and it became the default productivity mouse for a generation of knowledge workers. The MX Master 3S, released in 2022, is a refinement rather than a redesign — same shape, same shell, same battery, but with two meaningful upgrades: quiet clicks and a sensor that tracks on glass. We have been using the 3S as our daily driver for the past two months, across a Mac, a Windows desktop, and an iPad, to see whether those refinements justify a $99 purchase.</p>

      <p>This is the long-form version of our recommendation. For a comparison against eight other mice, see our <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-productivity/">best wireless mouse for productivity</a> roundup. Here we focus on what the 3S does well, where it still falls short, and whether it is worth the upgrade if you already own the older model.</p>

      <h2 id="pros-and-cons">Pros &amp; Cons</h2>
      <div class="pros-cons">
        <div class="pros">
          <h3>Pros</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>MagSpeed electromagnetic scroll wheel — still the best on any mouse</li>
            <li>8000 DPI Darkfield sensor tracks reliably on glass and glossy surfaces</li>
            <li>Quiet clicks are 90% quieter than the MX Master 3, ideal for shared spaces</li>
            <li>Logitech Flow controls three computers with one cursor and shared clipboard</li>
            <li>70-day battery life; USB-C charges while you keep using it</li>
            <li>Per-app button customization through Logi Options+</li>
            <li>Thumb wheel for horizontal scroll on wide spreadsheets and timelines</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="cons">
          <h3>Cons</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Right-handed only — no lefty version exists</li>
            <li>141 grams is heavy if you are coming from a gaming mouse</li>
            <li>Humpback shape favors palm grip; claw and fingertip grips feel cramped</li>
            <li>Logi Options+ required for Flow and per-app mapping adds bloatware risk</li>
            <li>USB-C port placement on the front means the cable sticks out while charging</li>
            <li>$99 is steep — the $40 M720 covers most of the same features</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="who-should-buy">Who Should Buy This — and Who Shouldn't</h2>
      <div class="audience">
        <div class="for">
          <h3>Great for</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Knowledge workers spending 6+ hours a day at a computer</li>
            <li>Anyone working across two or three devices — Mac, PC, iPad</li>
            <li>People who scroll long PDFs, code reviews, or spreadsheets daily</li>
            <li>Palm-grip users with medium to large hands (7 to 8.5 inches)</li>
            <li>Open-office workers who need quiet clicks to avoid annoying coworkers</li>
            <li>Anyone who works on glass desks or glossy tables without a mat</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="not-for">
          <h3>Skip it if</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You are a left-handed mouse user — Logitech makes no lefty version</li>
            <li>You are a gamer; the polling rate is too low and the mouse is too heavy</li>
            <li>You use a claw or fingertip grip exclusively</li>
            <li>You already own the MX Master 3 and use a desk pad — the upgrades are minor</li>
            <li>Your budget tops out at $40 — get the M720 Triathlon</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="detailed-review">Detailed Review</h2>

      <h3>MagSpeed Scroll Wheel: The Reason to Buy</h3>
      <p>The MagSpeed electromagnetic scroll wheel is the single feature that justifies the MX Master 3S over every other mouse we have used. It uses an electromagnet to switch between two modes: a tactile ratchet mode where each notch moves one line, and a free-spin mode where the wheel decouples entirely and spins freely for thousands of lines.</p>

      <p>The transition is automatic. A gentle roll moves line by line through code. A hard flick unlocks the wheel and spins through a 1,000-line PDF in under three seconds. You can also manually toggle modes with the button behind the wheel, but we left it on Smart Shift, which Logitech tunes to recognize intent. In two months of testing we never had it misfire on us.</p>

      <p>No other mouse on the market offers a scroll wheel this good. The MX Anywhere 3S uses the same MagSpeed mechanism in a smaller body. The Razer Basilisk V3 Pro has a similar free-spin wheel but it is heavier and bulkier, and the algorithm is less refined. Microsoft and SteelSeries still use mechanical wheels that cannot free-spin at all.</p>

      <p>Beside the main wheel, there is a horizontal thumb wheel on the side. It sounds like a gimmick until you use it on a wide spreadsheet or a video timeline. Being able to scroll right without holding Shift and rolling the wheel is genuinely useful, and we missed it on every mouse that did not have it.</p>

      <h3>8000 DPI Sensor: Glass Tracking Is Finally Real</h3>
      <p>Logitech bumped the sensor from 4000 DPI on the MX Master 3 to 8000 DPI on the 3S. In practice, you will never run it at 8000 DPI for productivity work — that is a sensitivity meant for high-resolution displays and very small movements. We run ours at 1600 DPI on a 4K display, which feels about right.</p>

      <p>The bigger upgrade is the Darkfield laser's ability to track on glass. The older MX Master 3 stuttered and skipped on glass desks, requiring a mat. The 3S tracks reliably. We tested it on a tempered glass desk, a glossy white mat, a fabric mousepad, and a wooden table. The 3S tracked cleanly on all of them. If you travel and end up working on hotel glass tables, this matters.</p>

      <p>The sensor's polling rate is 125 Hz over Bluetooth and 133 Hz over the included Logi Bolt receiver. For productivity work this is fine — you will not notice input lag at the desktop. Gamers will hate it, but this mouse was never built for them. If you need a gaming mouse, look elsewhere.</p>

      <h3>Quiet Clicks: The "S" Stands for Silent</h3>
      <p>The "S" in MX Master 3S stands for silent. Logitech claims the clicks are 90% quieter than the older MX Master 3, and that is not marketing fluff. We measured click noise with a decibel meter at 4 inches from the mouse: the older MX Master 3 registered around 58 dB per click, the 3S registered 48 dB. In an open office that difference is the gap between noticeable and invisible.</p>

      <p>The trade-off is that the clicks feel slightly mushier than the tactile snap of the older model. Some testers preferred the old click; most did not notice after a day. The right and left clicks are silent, but the side buttons are not — they make a normal clicking sound. If you remap gesture controls to the thumb buttons, be aware.</p>

      <p>If you work in a shared office, on calls, or next to a sleeping partner, the silent clicks are worth the price of admission alone. This is the single biggest reason to choose the 3S over the older 3.</p>

      <h3>Logitech Flow: Multi-Computer Control That Actually Works</h3>
      <p>Logitech Flow is the reason many people buy the MX Master 3S, and it is the reason it stays our top pick for productivity. Pair the mouse with up to three devices — over Bluetooth or the included Logi Bolt receiver — and install Logi Options+ on each computer. You then move the cursor off the edge of one screen and it appears on the next, exactly like a multi-monitor setup, except the monitors can be different computers.</p>

      <p>Flow also carries your clipboard across computers and lets you drag files between them over the local network. We tested dragging a 200 MB video from a Mac to a Windows PC and it worked without a hitch. Copy a URL on one machine and paste it on another. No other mouse we tested offers anything close.</p>

      <p>Setup takes about 10 minutes per machine. You need Logi Options+ installed on every computer, both computers on the same Wi-Fi network, and the mouse paired with each. We found the experience reliable on both Mac and Windows, though Logi Options+ does occasionally nag you to update firmware on the receiver.</p>

      <p>If you live on a single machine, Flow is not a reason to upgrade. But if you work on a Mac and a PC side by side — or a desktop and a laptop — Flow is the kind of feature you stop noticing because it just works.</p>

      <h3>Battery and USB-C Charging</h3>
      <p>Logitech rates the battery at 70 days per charge. In our testing, with eight hours of daily use, we averaged 58 to 62 days. The low-battery warning appears around day 55, which gives you about a week of grace before the mouse dies. Charging is over USB-C and you can keep using the mouse while it charges.</p>

      <p>A one-minute quick charge gives roughly three hours of use — enough to finish a meeting before hunting for a cable. A full charge from empty takes about an hour. The USB-C port is on the front of the mouse, which means the cable sticks out toward you while charging. It is a minor annoyance but not a deal-breaker.</p>

      <p>The battery is sealed inside the mouse and not user-replaceable. Logitech rates it for several years of charge cycles. We have not had ours long enough to verify long-term degradation, but the older MX Master 3 still holds a charge after three years for users we have spoken to, so we are not concerned.</p>

      <h3>Ergonomics and Build Quality</h3>
      <p>The MX Master 3S keeps the same sculpted humpback shape as the MX Master 3. The shape fills the palm without forcing the wrist into a flat position. After eight-hour days of use, our testers reported none of the fatigue hotspots we felt on flatter mice. The thumb rest is rubberized and angled slightly outward, which keeps the thumb off the desk.</p>

      <p>The shell is a soft-touch plastic that picks up fingerprints but feels premium in the hand. The build quality is excellent — there is no flex when you squeeze the mouse, no rattling when you shake it, and the buttons have a consistent click force across the entire surface. The weight is 141 grams, which sounds heavy but helps the mouse glide predictably across a desk pad.</p>

      <p>The mouse is right-handed only, and that is the single biggest criticism we can level at it. Left-handed users have to look elsewhere. If you are a lefty, our <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-work/">best wireless mouse for work guide</a> includes ambidextrous alternatives.</p>

      <p>We pair ours with a large desk pad (see our <a href="/reviews/best-desk-pad-large/">large desk pad review</a>) for consistent glide. The combination of a quality surface and a quality mouse is genuinely transformative — your hand stops fighting the input and the input gets out of the way.</p>

      <h3>Logi Options+ Software</h3>
      <p>Logi Options+ is required for Flow, per-app button mapping, and gesture controls. The software is free and works on both Mac and Windows. We have used it across two operating systems without major issues, though it does occasionally nag for firmware updates on the Logi Bolt receiver.</p>

      <p>The per-app mapping is genuinely useful. We set the thumb button to switch tabs in Chrome, mute on Zoom, and run a custom macro in VS Code. You can also adjust DPI, scroll speed, and Smart Shift sensitivity per application. Once you set it up, you stop thinking about it.</p>

      <p>The software does collect some usage data, which you can opt out of during setup. We opted out and have not noticed any impact on functionality.</p>

      <h2 id="comparison">How It Compares to the Competition</h2>
      <p>The MX Master 3S competes against the older MX Master 3, the smaller MX Anywhere 3S, and the budget M720 Triathlon. Here is how they stack up:</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Mouse</th>
            <th>Price</th>
            <th>Sensor (DPI)</th>
            <th>Quiet Clicks</th>
            <th>Glass Tracking</th>
            <th>Devices</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Logitech MX Master 3S</strong></td>
            <td>$99</td>
            <td>8000</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
