      <p>The <strong>MX Master 3</strong> (without the S) is still a great mouse and frequently goes on sale for $59 to $69. If you use a desk pad and do not need quiet clicks, it is a real bargain. But the 3S's glass tracking and silent clicks are worth the $20 premium for most people.</p>

      <p>The <strong>MX Anywhere 3S</strong> uses the same sensor and scroll wheel in a smaller body. It is the right choice for travelers and people with smaller hands. The trade-off is ergonomics — the smaller shape fatigues larger hands after about four hours.</p>

      <p>The <strong>M720 Triathlon</strong> is the budget champion at $40. It has a hyper-fast scroll wheel (mechanical, not MagSpeed), three-device pairing, and a comfortable shape. It is not as precise, the scroll wheel does not free-spin as smoothly, and the build quality feels cheaper. For the price it is remarkable.</p>

      <p>Pair the MX Master 3S with the <a href="/reviews/logitech-mx-keys-s-review/">Logitech MX Keys S</a> keyboard for a matching multi-device setup. We have a <a href="/reviews/best-wireless-mouse-productivity/">full comparison in our productivity mouse roundup</a> if you want to see how the 3S stacks up against non-Logitech alternatives.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-advice">Buying Advice</h2>
      <p>Buy the MX Master 3S at full price if you spend more than four hours a day at a computer and either work across multiple devices or hate loud clicks in shared spaces. The combination of MagSpeed scroll, glass tracking, and Flow is unmatched at this price.</p>

      <p>Wait for a sale if you can. Logitech runs promotions around Prime Day and Black Friday where the MX Master 3S drops to $69 to $79. We have seen it as low as $59 during clearance events. Set a price alert if you are not in a rush.</p>

      <p>Skip the MX Master 3 (without the S) unless it is heavily discounted. The older version lacks quiet clicks, has a weaker sensor, and struggles on glass. Paying $20 less for meaningfully worse tracking is not a good deal — unless you already use a desk pad.</p>

      <p>If you are upgrading from a basic mouse, consider pairing the MX Master 3S with the MX Keys S keyboard. Together they cost around $200, but they share the same multi-device Flow workflow, which means one-keyboard-one-mouse control across three computers. It is the most productive setup we have tested. If your laptop screen sits too low, add a <a href="/reviews/best-laptop-stand-desk/">laptop stand</a> to fix your neck posture at the same time.</p>

      <p>Avoid no-name clones on Amazon. Several look identical to the MX Master 3S at a quarter of the price, but the sensors skip, the scroll wheels break within months, and the batteries degrade fast. Stick with Logitech, Microsoft, Razer, or Keychron.</p>

